<section class="gallery">

  <div class="gallery">
  <h2>About Playa del Carmen</h2>
  <div class="description">
<mark>These are not stock photos, they were taken by members of our community.</mark>
    <p>

      Playa is a former sleepy fishing village at the shores of the Mexican Caribbean. In the last two decades it has seen explosive growth, drawing many young professionals from Mexico and abroad. It is home to significant community of ex-pats from Canada, Italy, Argentina, Israel, as well as young Mexican dreamers who come for a share of paradise. 
    </p>
  </div>
    <figure>
      <img src="img/gallery/tulum.jpg" alt="Composite of Chichen, Tulum and Cob√°" />
      <figcaption>Playa is surrounded by ancient Maya archeological sites. Tulum is just 40 minutes away and allows photographs of white sand beaches next to ancient Maya pyramids.</figcaption>
    </figure>

    <figure>
      <img src="img/gallery/5thave2.jpg" alt="The usual street in Playa del Carmen" />
      <figcaption>
        The local atmosphere is creative, friendly and laid-back. Visitors often get caught by surprise, thinking it will be a tourist trap. However, once they explore beyond the tourist areas, they often fall in love with the cultural diversity and their lifestyle.
      </figcaption>
    </figure>

    <figure>
      <img src="img/gallery/akumal.jpg" alt="Akumal" />
      <figcaption>Akumal is is a bay protected by a coral reef, just 30 mins away. This reef calms the waters which allows seaweed to grow in the bottom. Every day hundreds of sea turtles go there to feed and one can literally swim right next to them. </figcaption>
    </figure>

    <figure>
      <img src="img/gallery/cenote.jpg" alt="Cenote (sinkhole)" />
      <figcaption>There are numerous <em>cenotes nearby</em>. Cenotes are natural, freshwater sinkholes along the perimeter of the Chicxulub crater, which caused the mass extinction of dinosaurs. </figcaption>
    </figure>

    <figure>
      <img src="img/gallery/10th.jpg" alt="Playa's contrasts" />
      <figcaption>The city is very friendly to pedestrians. Most of Playa can be traversed walking, and offers interesting urban sights. One might find a modern condo next to a shack. Taxi fares are just $2-$3 USD (tips not usually given to taxi drivers).</figcaption>
    </figure>

    <figure>
      <img src="img/gallery/street.jpg" alt="Playa's architecture" />
      <figcaption>Playa has a local architecture that makes use of local materials.</figcaption>
    </figure>

    <figure>
      <img src="img/gallery/scuba.jpg" alt="Composite: Scuba Diving, Kite Surfing" />
      <figcaption>Scuba diving, yoga on the beach and kite surfing are popular passtimes in Playa</figcaption>
    </figure>

    <figure>
      <img src="img/gallery/5th.jpg" alt="5th Avenue" />
      <figcaption>La Quinta Avenida (5th Avenue) is a pedestrian walkway lined with shops, bars, cafes and restaurants. This is one of the main tourist hotspots.</figcaption>
    </figure>

    <figure>
      <img src="img/gallery/mamitas.jpg" alt="Mamitas Beach" />
      <figcaption>Mamitas Beach is Playa del Carmen's most popular beach. Various music and fashion festivals take place here throughout the year.</figcaption>
    </figure>

    <figure>
      <img src="img/gallery/12th.jpg" alt="12th Street" />
      <figcaption>12th street is the nightclub hotspot of Playa del Carmen. </figcaption>
    </figure>

    <figure>
      <img src="img/gallery/chichen.jpg" alt="Chichen Itza" />
      <figcaption>Chicen Itz√°, UNESCO World Heritage Site, is an ancient Maya city within a 3 hour drive of Playa</figcaption>
    </figure>

  </div>
</section>


